					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13189214#post-4650448</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13189214/scp-5307#post-4650448</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 16 May 2020 21:34:41 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>redredred</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5379342</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>There are two main approaches I've seen to articles that work well within a canon: those that actively try to further the story, and those that try to remain completely independent of the story but exist in the same universe. This tries to do both and thus falls flat on its face. Besides a lot of small issues that took me out of the experience<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-710339-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" >1</a></sup>, the core story here is extremely contrived and the characters are even more unrealistic. Aloysius talks like a Saturday-morning cartoon villain, so him casually murdering Mr. Thompson had no effect on me besides a slight chuckle at the absurdity of the entire situation.</p> <p>This is a -1 from me.</p> <div class="footnotes-footer"> <div class="title">Footnotes</div> <div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-710339-1"><a href="javascript:;" >1</a>. Why is the Discovery log not just collapsed into the Investigation log? Why are descriptions of the evidence gathered available to Level-2 Researchers, but can only be physically interacted with by Level-3 Researchers? If they're not able to interact or test them, then there's no point to even having them know it exists.</div> </div> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13189214#post-4619956</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13189214/scp-5307#post-4619956</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 28 Apr 2020 21:49:08 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>MaliceAforethought</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2902864</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>As far as I can tell, the core joke here is the fact that the word 'donk' sounds kinda funny &#8212; given that you've made a hub, several tales, and numerous other articles which go to great pains to spell that out, I really don't see the point of this article. It fails to create any memorable characters or elaborate on preexisting characters in an interesting way, and falls flat as either a piece of humour or a piece of worldbuilding.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13189214#post-4569533</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13189214/scp-5307#post-4569533</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 28 Mar 2020 19:51:10 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Rounderhouse</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4187885</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>This drags its feet in circles without going anywhere. The table is both purposeless and unfunny because the jokes are rote and expected, and the D-class comments are like one guy loudly laughing at the comedy set after every joke. The rest of the article relies on having the rest of the Donkman context like a bike relies on its wheels; it has no purpose or movement without it. It takes a thousand-odd words to reveal&#8230;. nothing to me. If the reveak was supposed to be about the guy or his wife or Donk's brother, it falls flat because you haven't done anything to make me like or even just be interested in these characters. If that character development is present in other Donkman works, I can't say, but that would just make the context problem worse. Donkman was funny as a one-off gag and now it's a dead horse &#8212; a dead donkey, as it were, being clubbed like a Canadian seal.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
